{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_herring_ver01/data/sn83045499/0039334233A/1937112401/0666.xml":{"full_text":"THE DAILY ALASKA EMPIRE\n\u201cALL THE NEWS ALL THE TIME'\n\u25a0S'\nVOL. LI., NO. 7648.\nJUNEAU, ALASKA, WEDNESDAY, NOVEMBER 24, 1937.\nMEMBER ASSOCIATED PRESS\nPRICE TEN CENTS\nPermanency of S. E. A laska A ir Base Looms\nNAVY BASE AT\nSITKA MAY BE\nINCREASED NOW\nSix Planes, with Tender,\nAlready There\u2014Other\nCraft May Be Sent\nNAVY DEPARTMENT\nANNOUNCES PLANS\nAnother Crew of Navy Men\nAre Stationed on Aleu\ntians for Purpose\nWASHINGTON, Nov. 24. The\nNavy Department discloses that six\npatrol planes and a naval tender\nhave been sent to Sitka. Alaska, to\nmake weather and serological ob\nservations this winter.\u201d\nAny move to set up a military\nbase in the Sitka area might have\nrepercussions in Tokyo but offic\nials said Japan would not have\ngrounds for formal objections, the\nNavy spokesman said.\nThe planes are long range, twin\nmotor bombers with a .crew of five\nto six men on each and with the\nminesweeper Lapwing as their ten\nder.\nThe planes flew unannounced\nfror# Seattle.\nStressing that the purpose of the\nestablishment of a winter base was\nscientific rather than military. Na\nval officials said the Sitka base\nwas in addition to the smaller win\nter base already set up farther west\nin the Aleutians. Six men have\nbeen taken there by the cruiser\nPortland and will remain all winter.\nIt is expected they will make ob\nservations in the upper air by means\nof small radio equipped captive bal\nloons.\nWith the crew of the Lapwing and\nmechanics for planes, the Navy will\nhave more than 70 men at Sitka.\nIt is not known yet. but this force\nmay be increased. The planes now\n(here are already working in con\njunction w'ith the Sitka radio sta\ntion\nConfessed Slayer\nAttempts Suicide\nIn His Jail Cell\nLOS LUNAS, New Mexico, Nov.\n24.\u2014In a state of hysterics after at\ntempting a jail cell suicide by hang\ning which was thwarted by other\nprisoners, W. B. Cassidy, 43, Socorro\nbusiness man, will be taken to the\nState Penitentiary at Santa Pe for\nsake keeping.\nCassidy recently confessed to the\nlov\u00ab killing of Rose Garcia, 19,\nand burying her body in a sand\ngraye. She was a servant in his\nlion*.\nCtossidy tried to hang himself\nwith, a chain taken from his cot.\nDIVIDEND\nDECLARED\nSEATTLE, Nov. 24.\u2014The Alaska\nPacific Salmon Corporation an\nnounces a semi-annual dividend of\n50 cents a share on preferred stock\nto be paid December 1. The divi\ndend will amount to approximately\n$10,000. _\nA Thanksgiving Thought\nt\nr\nwe ve\nOLi\u00ab nation*\nnroeeTHEft,\nSA^UBL.\nFORD ASSAULT\nCASE CHARGES\nARE DISMISSED\nCircuit Judge Rules Evi\ndence Produced Not\nSufficient for Trial\nDETROIT, Mich,, Nov. 24,\u2014Cir\ncuit Court Judge Lester Mill has\ndismissed the charges ol felonious\nassault against the Ford Motor\nCompany and eight individuals as\nthe result of the beating of United\nAutomobile Workers and organiz\ners near the Ford Rogue plant last\nMay 25.\nJudge Mill ruled that the evidence\nproduced at the preliminary hearing\nwas not sufficient to warrant hold\ning the defendants for trial.\nMinister Is\ni Convicted of\nKilling Woman\nPITTSFIELD, 111., Nov. 24.\u2014The\nRev. C. E: Newton has been con\nvicted of the slaying of a loyal\nchurch worker. The jury fixed\npunishment at life imprisonment.\nThe Missouri country preacher\nhad pleaded he was. a victim of cir\ncumstances in the brutal hammer\nslaying last July of Mrs. Dennis\nKelly, 45, of Paris, Missouri.\nStock Exchange\nWar Threatened\nBy Fed. Forces\nUltimatum Is Made Chair\nman of Securities\nCommission\nWASHINGTON, Nov. 24, The\nFederal Securities Commission\nbluntly told the officials of the New\nYork Stock Exchange to get ready\nfor a Federal house cleaning unless\nWall Streeters themselves stabilize\nthe stock market.\nChairman W. C. Douglas accuses\nprofessional traders of accentuating\nthe ups and downs of the securities\nmarket and called on them to sur\nrender their control of the Exchange\nto persons \u201cwho have clearer public\nresponsibilities.\u201d\nThe statement surprised Wall\nStreet operators, many of whom in-;\nterpreted it as an open declaration;\nof war in an attempt to place the\nresponsibility for market breaks on!\nthe Stock Exchange.\n'c. D. A. INITIATION\nIS HELD YESTERDAY\nInitiation was held at the meet\ning of the Catholic Daughters of\nAmerica last night, when Mrs.\nClarence Wise, Mrs. Charles Dev\nlin, and Mrs. Howard Hayes became\nmembers of the organization,\nj As a special event of the even\ning, the C. D. A. presented a wed\nj ding gift to Mrs. Peter Bond who\nwas married in Wrangell recently.\nMrs. Walter G. Hellan presided at\nI the business meeting. _\nNEW BUSINESS\nSLANT TAKEN\nBY ONE LEADER\nSuggests Method for Get\nting Reconciled with\nAdministration\nNEW YORK, Nov, 24.\u2014Wendell\nWilkie, President of the Common\nwealth and Southern Corporation,\nsaid that \"as a compromise, in or\nder to bring reconciliation between\nthe Administration and private\nbusiness,\u201d he is willing to adopt in\nthe future \"prudent investment\"\ntheory on valuation of properties\nand rate making.\nWilkie is head of the country\u2019s\nlargest holding combinations.\nWilkie, further stated: \"1 would\nrecommend that utilities should be\nvalued as of the rate rules laid\ndown by the Supreme Court which\nhave been in effect for 40 years\nand tiie prudent investment theory\nshould be adopted hereafter.\u201d\nWilkie conferred with President\nRoosevelt yesterday and said he un\nderstood the prudent investment\ntheory valuation means \"whether\nthe investment is prudently made.\u201d\nHOW BIG? GOAT\u2014IT\nA beautiful rumor continually\nfloated into The Empire office\ntoday about a big goat.\nIt is understood that Paul Hudon.\nof the Standard Machine Shop, and\nGeorge Skuse, have returned to\ntown from a hunting trip with a\ngoat so big\u2014it could not be as big\nas the rumors.\n$25,000 FIRE AT\nANCHORAGE;\nHANGAR BURNS\nOne Plane, Five Motors,\nPishing Gear, Supplies\nGo Up in Blaze\nANCHORAGE, Alaska. Nov. 24.\u2014\nA five destroyed A1 Jones' hangar\nwith damage estimated at $25,000.1\nOne airplane, five airplane motors,\nparts of several other planes, val- j\nunble fishing gear and a large stock\nof supplies were burned in the fire, j\nThe fire started while workmen\nwere using fire pots to dry out the\ntail of a plane preparatory to paint\ning it.\nJones is the owner of the Anchor\nage Airways.\nfloydTjarlisle\nSAYS PRESIDENT\nRIGHT ON POWER:\nAnnounces Edison Consoli\ndated Will Spend Mil-\nlions, Development\nWASHINGTON, Nov. 24. Floyd\nCarlisle, Chairman of the Consoli\ndated Edison Company reported, af\nter a White House conference that\nhe is in substantial agreement with\nPresident Roosevelt\u2019s power views.\nCarlisle's company expects to co\noperate in the new construction\nprogram by spending $100,000,000\nin the next two years.\nChairman Carlisle gave added in\ndications of progress in the Presi\ndent\u2019s efforts to meet what Roose\nvelt calls \"a crying need for ex\npansion\" in the power industry, to\naid the general business outlook.\n\"I think the fears of government\ncompetition are very much lessened\nby the discus^ons that have taken\nplace,\u201d said Carlisle to newsmen,\nadding that he was not in dissent\nwith the President's general views\nregarding the basis of rate mak\ning.\nFDR TO EhT\nTURKEY IN\nWHITE HOUSE\nWASHINGTON. Nov. 24. Al\nthough President Roosevelt has\nbeen In office nearly five years, he\nand Mrs. Roosevelt will eat their\nfirst Thanksgiving Day turkey in\nthe White House tomorrow.\nIt has been customary for the\nPresident to visit the Warm Springs,\nGeorgia, Foundation, on Thanks\ngiving Day, but this visit has been\npostponed until he recovers fully\nfrom tooth infection. He missed\nthe Thanksgiving Day dinner at\nWarm Springs last year because\nhe was enroute to Buenos Aires\nto attend the Peace Conference.\nThe change in the arrangement\nfound most of the children already\nhaving made their plans for din\nners elsewhere so there will be no\nfamily reunion.\nBROWN TO KETCHIKAN\nR. R. Brown, Manager of the\nUnited Pood Company, sailed for\nKetchikan on the Dellwood in con\nnection with the company's busi\nness in that city.\nNanking Is\nAir Raided;\nManv Dead\n_ I\nSHANGHAI, Nov. 24. The\nJapanese spokesman announces\nthat bombing planes have raid\ned Nanking and it is reported\nthat 40 civilians were killed.\nThe announcement coincides\nwith foreign confirmation that\nthe long awaited Russian manu\nfactured planes have arrived at\nNanking to bolster the Chinese\nAir Forces.\nThe Japanese raid is believed\nto have been an attempt to\nsmash the new craft quickly.\nEarlier reports state that 34\nAmericans and 28 other foreign\ners remaining in Nanking asked\nthe Japanese to make their\nquarters a neutral zone and pre\nvent possible destruetion of the\nquarters by bomb shells.\nThe Japanese authorities said\nthey favored the proposal In\nprincipal but there were mili\ntary considerations which the\nair force and military had to\ntake in account.\nReports from Hongkong said\nJapanese planes have bom-\nbarded Canton and about 100\ncivilians are said to have been\nkilled.\nPassengers Are Flying\nTo Juneau to Connect\nWith States Bound Ship\nBusiness Taxes\nTo Be Eased by\nNew Legislation\nModification of Corporate\nSurplus lax Is\nProposed\nWASHINGTON. Nov. 24\u2014Admin\nistration officials have talked with\nCongressional leaders with regards\nto the possibility of quick action to\nassure business be eased of its tax\nburden.\nChairman Harrison, of the Senate\nFinance Committee, who up to this\nmorning insisted nothing could bo\ndone immediately on the tax ques\ntion, conferred with Mariner Ec\ncles, chairman of the Reserve Board\nand later with Treasury officials.\nHe reports two proposals were dis\ncussed.\nOne proposal is for simultaneous\nannouncement by Roosevelt Con\ngres-'onal leaders that business tax\nes be revised and the second is that\nquick action be taken during this\nsession on the bill being framed by\nthe House Tax subcommittee to\nmodify corporate surplus tax.\nThe House Agriculture Committee\nhas completed drafting its Crop\nControl bill, companion to the Sen\nate measure.\nThe House in convening, was\nmarked by tactics of delay from\nopponents of the Wages and Hour\nbill, who forced a half hour roll\ncall.\nHOLDEN GOES TO\nPOLARIS TAKU;\nBUT NOT SITKA\nAlex Holden flew his wheel\nequipped Fairchild 71 to the Polar\nis-Taku mine today, taking two\nmen, MacDougall and Collins, and\nj returned with D. C. Sharpstone\nand four other passengers,\nj The Sitka scheduled flight was\ncancelled because of high winds\nI in uhe islands, but will be made\ni tomorrow, weather permitting.\nANCHORAGE. Alaska, Nov. 24.\u2014\nAlaskans, alarmed by the steam- J\n.ship tie-up. are rushing In unu.su\nully large numbers to book passage\noutside on the Star Air Lines.\nIt is said one tri-motored plane\ncarrying 12 passengers will leave\nfor Juneau today to make connec\ntions with a states-bound vessel.\nThe airways officials said passage\nrequests have been received from\nmore than 30 persons.\nFORMER P. M. G.\nBURLESON DIES\nIN TEXAS HOME:\nAUSTIN. Texas, Nov. 24.\u2014Albert\nSidney Burleson, 74, Postmaster\nGeneral in the cabinet of President\nWilson, is dead at his home here\nand funeral services are planned'\nfor late this afternoon.\nHe is survived by his widow,\nthree daughters, two sisters and six\ngrandchildren.\nH. M. TOWNER\nPASSES AWAY\nCORNING, Iowa, Nov, 24.\u2014Judge\nHorace Mann Towner, former Gov\nernor of Puerto Rico and former Re\npublican Congressman from Iowa,\ndied last night. His condition had\nbeen serious since early in the fall.\nTowner returne dhere in 1929 af\nter serving six years as Governor\nof Puerto Rico.\nMRS. HAYES PLANS\nTO LEAVE ON NORAH\nMrs. A. B. Hayes, who has been\nvisiting in Juneau for the past few\nweeks, will sail south aboard the\nPrincess Norah if passage is avail\nable.\ni Mrs. Hayes has been visiting here\njwith her mother. Mrs. R. P. Nelson,\nher sister and two brothers. She is\nI to return to her home in Seattle.\nSTEAMERS TO\nSAIL AT ONCE\nFOR NORTHLAND\nNorth Sea Scheduled for\nFriday with Yukon\nLeaving Saturday\nUNION WITHDRAWS\nROTATION DEMANDS\nMen Return to Work Just\nas if Settlement Is\nPermanent One\nSEATTLE, Nov. 21. The\nshipping strike which has\ntied up Alaska steamers for\nsix days is ended.\nOperators of the three lines,\nAlaska Steamship Company,\nNorthland Transpor t a t i o n\nCompany and Alaska Trans\nportation Company, announc\ned at noon today, that a settle\nment of the dispute between\nthe three lines serving the\nnorthern territory and the\nMarine Cooks and Stewards\nhad been made.\nThen men will return to\nwork under former conditions\nof employment.\nMax Watson, business agent\nof the union, said the settle\nment is tentative.\nThe union withdrew the de\nmand for rotation of cooks,\nstewards and waiters.\nWatson said: \u201cWe are going\nahead w'ith plans to return to\nwork as if the settlement was\npermanent.\u201d\nFinal decision of permanen\ncy awaits the arrival of the\nYukon from Alaska tomorrow\nbut it is understood here that\nthe men aboard the Yukon are\nalmost unanimously against a\nwalkout.\nFollowing announc e m on t\nthat the dispute was ended, it\nwas stated that the North Sea\nwill sail for Southeast Alaska\nports Friday morning at 10\no\u2019clock or at 9 o\u2019clock in the\nevening, it all depending how\nfreight arrives at the wharf,\nand the Yukon will sail for\nSoutheast and Southwest Al\naska ports at 9 o\u2019clock Satur\nday morning.\nSPEEDY SETTLEMENT\nSEATTLE. Nov. 24.\u2014Federal La\nbor Conciliator E. P. Marsh last\nnight forecast a speedy settlement\nof the dispute which has tied-up Al\naska shipping.\nMarsh adjourned the second con\nference of operators of the steamers\nand representatives of the Marine\nCooks and Stewards Association,\nsubject to call, sometime today.\nMarsh said: \u2018Both sides are mak\ning real efforts to get together. I\nanticipate definite results within 24\nhours.\"\n93,000 Jews Leave\nBERLIN Jewish emigration\nfrom Germany since Adolf Hitler\ncame into power in 1933 totals 93,000\npersons, according to the Jewish Ag\nency. Of the total, 38,500 Jews have\ngone to Palestine.\nii II, '^i pi t iiii\u2014m","height":"26716","width":"20904"}}
